Introduction

On the tidyverse

The tidyverse is a collection of R packages designed for data science. Developed with high standards of coding practices and software development, these packages form a consistent ecosystem to handle and visualise data. In this practical, we will mostly rely on the following packages:

  • dplyr for handling data, making new variables, building summaries, number-crunching

  • tidyr to re-arrange tidy/data

  • ggplot2 to visualise data

  • forcats to handle categorical data (factors)

  • magrittr for the piping operator (%>%)

Most of these functionalities are summarised in handy cheatsheets. We provide links to the most relevant ones below:

  • basics of R (not tidyverse, but they remain very useful)

  • data transformation using dplyr

  • data visualisation using ggplot2

  • handling factors using forcats

Exploring outbreak data

What we will do today

This practical will use different outbreak data to illustrate how the various packages mentioned above can be combined to explore outbreak data. Amongst other things, we will learn how to:

  • get an overview of a dataset
  • make simple epidemic curves
  • count cases by geographic units, gender, or any other groups
  • build age pyramids
  • derive and compare group proportions
  • make beautiful and informative graphs

How this document works

This practical will take you through initial exploratory analyses of different datasets. Some parts will be used merely to illustrate a technical point (e.g.how to count cases by different groups), some will focus more on the epidemiological meaning of a result, and some will do both. These analyses are merely meant as a guide, and are by no means an exhaustive exploration of the data. Be curious: feel free to ask new questions and try to answer them. In all instances, try to first answer your own questions: try/error is a great way to learn R. But if you feel stuck, do not hesitate to questions to the demonstrators: they are here to help.

In this practical, most command lines are provided, but not all. In the few instances where code is not provided, you will typically need to re-use and adapt previous code to produce the result requested. In most cases, copy-paste should be sufficient to reproduce the results.

However, it is important that you understand what the code does. Look at relevant documentation, try tweaking the code, experiment, and do not hesitate to ask questions. It is not essential to go through all examples to illustrate important points, so take your time, especially if you are new to R. Also note that the solutions provided are by not means the only options for solving a given problem - feel free to explore alternatives and discuss them with the trainers.

Outbreak 1: Measles in Hagelloch, Germany, 1861

For this first outbreak, we use a dataset distributed in the R package outbreaks, which contains a linelist of measles cases of an outbreak which took place in Hagellock, Germany, in 1861 (Oesterle 1993 ; Neal and Roberts 2004). The datasets name is measles_hagelloch_1861. For more information on the data, type ?measles_hagelloch_1861.

Loading the data

We first load required packages and the data, which we save in an object x for convenience.


# load packages
library(tidyverse) # this loads all tidyverse packages
library(outbreaks) # for datasets
library(ggrepel)   # additional features for ggplot2



# load the data, convert to tibble and store as 'x'
x <- measles_hagelloch_1861 %>%
  tibble()

Building an epicurve

One of the first things to do when looking at outbreak data is plot case incidence over time to produce an epidemic curve (or epicurve). There are several packages to make this easy, which will be seen later in the course. Here, we manually build these curves for practice. The approach is to:

  • calculate incidence: count cases by day (using dates of symptom onset, or prodrome here)

  • basic plot: plot the corresponding case counts over time; this is what you would do to have a quick look at the results, for yourself

  • nice plot: customise the epicurve plot to make it nice and share results

Tips to customise graphs

  • Using custom colors: nice colors can go a long way towards communicating results; one way to customise colors is to use HTML color codes, for instance using this tool; all hex codes e.g.#777284 can be used in R; also note there are professional designer tools to create consistent color palettes, such as paletton.com (see palettonr for importing these palettes)

  • Specifying data formats: date formats in R use key words, e.g.%d for the digit of the day, %B for the full month, etc.; details on these keywords are hidden in the documentation of ?strptime

x_counts <- x %>%
  count(date_of_prodrome)

  ggplot(aes(x = date_of_prodrome, y = n)) +
  geom_col()


# same plot with some customisation; note that we save the date scale as it
# will be re-used later; see ?strptime for date formats

scale_dates <- scale_x_date(date_labels = "%d %b %Y")

x_counts %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date_of_prodrome, y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#DF7416") +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_dates +
  labs(title = "Epicurve of the Hagelloch 1861 measle outbreak",
       x = "Date of onset",
       y = "Number of cases (daily)")

Looking at age, gender, and class distributions

Here, we will look at the number of cases by age, gender, and class years. Note that we treat age as a categorical variable, but we could equally treat it as a quantitative variable, in which case we would use other geom for data visualisation, such as geom_histogram or geom_density.


# plotting the age distribution
ggplot(x, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Age distribution",
       x = "Age in years",
       y = "Number of cases")



# plotting the age distribution with gender
ggplot(x, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = gender)) +
  labs(title = "Age distribution by gender",
       x = "Age in years",
       y = "Number of cases")



# adding class information
ggplot(x, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = gender)) +
  facet_grid(class ~ .) +
  labs(title = "Age distribution by gender (split by class)",
       x = "Age in years",
       y = "Number of cases")

The graph above essentially contains all information we need, but we can customise it slightly to make it clearer, for instance by recoding the gender information and accounting for missing data using fct_recode from the forcats package:


x <- x %>%
  mutate(new_gender = fct_recode(gender,
                                 female = "f",
                                 male = "m"),
         new_gender = fct_explicit_na(new_gender, "missing"))
x %>% count(gender, new_gender) # sanity check
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   gender new_gender     n
##   <fct>  <fct>      <int>
## 1 f      female        83
## 2 m      male          94
## 3 <NA>   missing       11

scale_gender <- scale_fill_manual("",
                                  values = c(female = "#54A97B",
                                             male = "#8473A0",
                                             missing = "grey"))
ggplot(x, aes(x = age)) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = new_gender)) +
  facet_grid(class ~ .) +
  scale_gender +
  labs(title = "Age distribution by gender (split by class)",
       x = "Age in years",
       y = "Number of cases")


Exercise: use the same approach to create a new variable new_class, which will recode class so that:

  • 1 becomes class_1

  mutate(new_class = forcats::fct_recode(class,

Building age pyramids

Age-gender distributions are usually displayed as age pyramids. The package apyramid, developped as part of the R4epis project, provides a nice implementation for these graphs.


# load apyramid
library(apyramid)

# define age as a factor
x <- x %>%
  mutate(age_fct = factor(age, levels = 0:15))

# make plot
x %>%
  age_pyramid(age_group = age_fct, split_by = gender)


# to try: use 'new_gender' instead of 'gender'; why is the graph different?

One interesting feature is that additional, non-binary data can be added as colors (see ?age_pyramid for the argument to use).

x %>%
  filter(new_gender != "missing") %>%
  droplevels() %>%

Looking at classes dynamics over time

To look at class dynamics over time, we calculate incidence for each day and class. This is made simple by the fact that count can use several variables, as illustrated below:


# counts cases by dates and class
x_counts_class <- x %>%
  count(date_of_prodrome, new_class)

# custom color scale
scale_class <- scale_fill_manual("",
                                 values = c(preschool = "#E8AD7E",
                                            class_1 = "#D37830",
                                            class_2 = "#8E5B33"))

       subtitle = "Broken down by classes",
       x = "Date of onset",
       y = "Number of cases (daily)")

Explanation:

The epidemic curve suggests that classes might have impacted the spread of the disease: we first see a flare-up in class 1, then in class 2 and the preschool class. However, this is far from conclusive at this stage: transmission chains data would be needed to further investigate how the class structure impacted transmission.

Outbreak 2: Ebola virus disease in Sierra Leone, 2014

This dataset represents a subset of the large Ebola outbreak which took place in West Africa in 2013-2016. The dataset we analyse is a linelist of cases from Sierra Leone published by Fang et al. (2016), which covers the period 2014-05-18 to 2015-09-13, and includes both confirmed and suspected cases.

Importing the data

For this example, we will import data from an Excel spreadsheet using the package rio and its handy function import. This function automatically detects the type of file from its extension and uses the appropriate method to import the data into R.

To read the data in, follow these steps:

  1. in your current R project, create a folder called data/ (all lower case)

  2. download the data (file: ebola_sierraleone_2014.xlsx) from the moodle, and save it in the data/ folder

Tip This dataset is also available in the outbreaks package under the same name. 

# find path to data
path_to_file <- here::here("data", "ebola_sierraleone_2014.xlsx")
path_to_file
## [1] "/home/thibaut/dev/teaching/soar21/day1/practicals/data/ebola_sierraleone_2014.xlsx"

# read file in and convert to tibble
x <- path_to_file %>%
  rio::import() %>% 
  tibble()

# fix dates (we don't have date-time)
x <- x %>%
  mutate(date_of_onset = as.Date(date_of_onset),
         date_of_sample = as.Date(date_of_sample))

# note: fast alternative to fix all dates in one go is:
# x %>% mutate(across(contains("date"), as.Date))

Making a basic epidemic curve

We use the same approach as in the previous example to derive an epidemic curve by date of symptom onset:


# calculate case incidence
x_counts <- x %>%
  count(date_of_onset)

# basic plot
x_counts %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date_of_onset, y = n)) +
  geom_col()

Breaking cases by district

In the following, we provide a breakdown of cases by district (the coarser geographic unit), by providing:

  1. case counts by district, and case status
  2. plotting the resulting counts
  3. calculating the percentage of the confirmed/suspected cases coming from each district

# 1. derive case counts by status and district
# (note that we don't save the result)
x %>% count(status, district)

# 2. make a plot
x %>%
  count(status, district) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = district, x = n)) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_col(aes(fill = status)) +
  scale_fill_manual("Case status",
                    values = c(confirmed = "#777284",
                               suspected = "#ACA6BC")) +
  labs(title = "Ebola cases by district",
       subtitle = "Ebolo outbreak, Sierra-Leone, 2014 ",
       x = "Number of cases",
       y = "")


# 3. % of total confirmed cases by district
x %>%
  count(status, district) %>%
  spread(status, n) %>%
  mutate(perc_confirmed = 100 * confirmed / sum(confirmed),
         perc_suspected = 100 * suspected / sum(suspected))

We can also generate separate epidemic curves by districts. As there are slightly too many districts for useful use of colors, we use facet_wrap to generate separate plots.


# counts by district
x_counts_districts <- x %>%
  group_by(date_of_onset, district) %>%
  count()

# plot
x_counts_districts %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date_of_onset, y = n)) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~ district, nrow = 3) +
  theme(strip.text.y = element_text(angle= 0)) +
  labs(title = "Epicurves by district",
       subtitle = "Daily incidence, by dates of onset",
       x = "",
       y = "Daily cases")

Comparing cases across disticts and chiefdoms



Exercise: examine the code and figures below, and interpret the results; what do these figures show? what does it potentially say about surveillance in different districts / chiefdoms?




x_status_district <- x %>%
  count(district, status) %>%
  spread(status, n, fill = 0)


x_status_district %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = suspected, y = confirmed)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_label_repel(aes(label = district)) +
  theme_bw()


x_status_chiefdom <- x %>%
  count(district, chiefdom, status) %>%
  spread(status, n, fill = 0)

x_status_chiefdom %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = suspected, y = confirmed)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_label_repel(
    data = filter(
      x_status_chiefdom,
      suspected > 250 | confirmed > 250),
    aes(label = chiefdom, fill = district)) +
  theme_bw()

Explanation:

We would normally expect numbers of confirmed and suspected cases to be positively correlated, and this is what we actually observe at a district level. When looking at this relationship at a chiefdom level, however, we find that there are a few outliers not following this relationship at all: some chiefdoms have a lot more confirmed than suspected cases, or the other way around. This could reflect different things: different epicase definition (which would need harmonising), or different testing capacity (with less confirmed cases where testing is limited), or poorer surveillance in locations with many suspected cases (e.g.if these are akeen to community deaths).

Age and gender distributions

As previously, we use the package apyramid to visualise age-gender demographics amongst confirmed and suspected cases. However, rather than using actual ages as we did before, we will now define age classes. Several approaches can be used, depending on whether we want specific age classes, or merely a limited number of bins to summarise the data with. Here, we opt for the latter, using a small ad-hoc function autocut which will partition data into a given number of equally-sized bins:

# We define a function to break ages into bins
## 'x' is a vector of number (ages)
## 'n' is an ideal number of bins seeked; defaults to 5
autocut <- function(x, n = 5) {
  cut(x, breaks = pretty(x, n = n), right = TRUE, include.lowest = TRUE)
}

# Example of how it works
tibble(age = 0:11) %>%
  mutate(age_group = autocut(age))
## # A tibble: 12  2
##      age age_group
##    <int> <fct>    
##  1     0 [0,2]    
##  2     1 [0,2]    
##  3     2 [0,2]    
##  4     3 (2,4]    
##  5     4 (2,4]    
##  6     5 (4,6]

What does this graph suggest in terms of gender distribution across districts? Do you find evidence for a specific bias?

To investigate this further, we shall compare the proportions of males across districts. To this end, we will need to use a function which will compute the confidence intervals for each proportion. This is achieved by the ad-hoc function prop_ci, defined below. Note that you do not need to understand the underlying code at this stage. Simply copy-paste the code and the function will work.

#' This function uses `binom.test` to derive estimates of the 95% CI for
#' proportions.
#'
#' @param k number of successes
#'
#' @param n number of trials
#'
#' @param conf confidence level, defaults to 0.95
#'
#' @param result a `character` vector indicating which bounds of the confidence
#'   interval to return: can be `"lower"`, or `"upper"`, or `"both"`
#'
#' @author Thibaut Jombart
#' 

prop_ci <- function(k, n,
                    result = c("both", "lower", "upper"),
                    conf = 0.95) {
  if(n == 0){
    out = c(0,1)
  } else {
    out <- binom.test(k, n, conf.level = conf)$conf.int
    result <- match.arg(result)
  }
  if (result == "both") {
    result <- c("lower", "upper")
  }
  names(out) <- c("lower", "upper")
  out <- out[result]
  
  out
}

prop_ci <- Vectorize(prop_ci)


# Some examples
prop_ci(10, 30)
##            [,1]
## lower 0.1728742
## upper 0.5281200
prop_ci(100, 300)
##            [,1]
## lower 0.2802048
## upper 0.3897924
prop_ci(10, 30, "lower")
##     lower 
## 0.1728742
prop_ci(10, 30, "upper")
##   upper 
## 0.52812

In the following, we:

  • derive counts by gender and district
  • calculate the proportion of males in each district
  • derive the associated confidence intervals

gender_stats <- x %>%
  filter(!is.na(new_sex)) %>%
  count(district, new_sex) %>%
  spread(new_sex, n) %>%
  mutate(total = female + male,
         p_male = male / total,
         p_low = prop_ci(male, total, "lower"),
         p_high = prop_ci(male, total, "upper"))
gender_stats

How would you interpret these results? If you had observed this during the response, what follow-up action would you have recommended?

Explanation:

When looking at raw numbers, it is not clear if there is a bias towards a particular gender in some locations. However, the proportion of males and its confidence interval shows that in two districts (Western Urban and Kono), the proportion of males amongst cases is significantly higher than in a balanced sex ratio. This could be indicative of a genuine difference, but also reflect a selection bias in testing or surveillance, which should be investigated.
